column18: Welcome to this scientific study about media use and political opinions. The study is led by Bernhard Clemm from the European University Institute, Florence, Italy.     The questionnaire will take approximately 5 minutes. Upon successful completion you will be re-directed to Dynata for payment. Your data will be anonymized and only analysed according to US data protection law.     The quality of our data is important. We therefore ask you to take your time. Please respond to questions attentively and do not leave the questionnaire while responding.       Should you have any question or feedback after completing the survey, you can contact the study author via bernhard.clemm@eui.eu.

column65: Many thanks for your reponses! To complete this survey, please read through the information below.    We have told you before that this study was about media use and political opinions. But we also wanted to learn how people judge academic research. For that purpose, we randomly assigned participants to different groups that saw slightly different reports regarding CO2 emissions and affirmative action. Therefore, we would like to give you the real data concerning these two reports.    CO2 emission standards  The described research did not actually happen. To our knowledge, there is no research indicating that stricter motor vehicle CO2 emission standards might lead to an overall increase of CO2 emissions because of higher use of public transportation.     Affirmative action  The question whether affirmative action leads to more or less black lawyers is disputed. The described study by Professor Richard Sander is real (Stanford Law Review 57 (2): 367–483) and claims that affirmative action hurts black students due to the overly competitive environments in more prestigious schools. In contrast, academics Ayres and Brooks published a study claiming that eliminating affirmative action would not increase the number of black lawyers by 7.9 percent, as Sander's study had claimed, but that it would instead reduce the number of lawyers by about 12.7 percent (Stanford Law Review 72: 1807-1854). You can find more information about the debate on Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Sander     To test our ideas properly, it was important not to give you these facts earlier. We hope you understand our approach.      If you feel like leaving some feedback on the study, you can do so below. Otherwise, proceed to complete the survey.

column65: The biggest problem about reading a paragraph in a survey and then trying to decide if it is accurate or not is that you may miss facts or problems with the study. Research is good, but when papers are written, the authors do tend to work the data to fit what they want to prove. And, it's important to think critically when reading information and to try and read documents from a number of people and places, not just one, as done with this survey.

They tend to be much more supportive of law students, ans many law students are more comfortable there due to the cultural connection that makes them feel they matter more.In the case of the emmissions research, there was no mention of the types of cars people were driving.
